('computer-science:1-2-4-data-storage-numbers:mcq:29d37313', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:1-2-4-data-storage-numbers', '1.2.4 Data Storage: Numbers', 'mcq', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "A value in an 8-bit register undergoes a logical LEFT shift of 3 places, and no 1-bits are lost off the end. What is the effect on the stored value?", "options": ["It is multiplied by 8", "It is divided by 8", "It is multiplied by 3", "It stays exactly the same value"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "Each place shifted left doubles the value, so shifting left 3 places multiplies it by 2³ = 8 (as long as no significant bits are lost off the end)."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:1-2-4-data-storage-numbers:mcq:22492a50', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:1-2-4-data-storage-numbers', '1.2.4 Data Storage: Numbers', 'mcq', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "A logical RIGHT shift of 2 places is performed on an 8-bit value, and the two right-most bits shifted off are both 1s. What happens to those two bits?", "options": ["They are permanently lost, so the result is no longer an exact ÷4 of the value", "They move around and reappear as the new left-most bits at the opposite end of the register", "They are stored separately by the CPU so no data is actually lost", "They cause the shift operation to fail and return an error message"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "A logical shift simply discards any bit pushed off the end — it does not wrap around. If those lost bits were 1s, the result is no longer an exact division by 4."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:1-2-4-data-storage-numbers:tf:0d272629', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:1-2-4-data-storage-numbers', '1.2.4 Data Storage: Numbers', 'tf', 'tf', 1, '{"question": "The largest denary value that can be stored using 8 bits is 255."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": true, "explain": "Correct — 8 bits give 2⁸ = 256 possible values, counted from 0, so the highest is 255."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:1-2-4-data-storage-numbers:tf:ad899195', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:1-2-4-data-storage-numbers', '1.2.4 Data Storage: Numbers', 'tf', 'tf', 1, '{"question": "Hexadecimal digits run from 0-9 and then continue upward as G, H, I, J, K and L."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": false, "explain": "Hexadecimal only needs 16 digits in total: 0-9, then the letters A-F (representing 10-15). There is no G digit in hexadecimal."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:1-2-4-data-storage-numbers:tf:e2060a58', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:1-2-4-data-storage-numbers', '1.2.4 Data Storage: Numbers', 'tf', 'tf', 1, '{"question": "The most significant bit (MSB) of an 8-bit binary number is the right-most bit."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": false, "explain": "The opposite is true — the MSB is the LEFT-most bit, carrying the largest place value (128). The right-most bit (value 1) is the least significant bit (LSB)."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:1-2-4-data-storage-numbers:tf:05b8becd', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:1-2-4-data-storage-numbers', '1.2.4 Data Storage: Numbers', 'tf', 'tf', 1, '{"question": "A logical left shift by 3 places multiplies the original value by 8, provided no significant bits are lost."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": true, "explain": "Correct — each place shifted left doubles the value, so 3 places gives 2³ = 8 times the original value."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:1-2-4-data-storage-numbers:tf:eb8a0c2e', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:1-2-4-data-storage-numbers', '1.2.4 Data Storage: Numbers', 'tf', 'tf', 1, '{"question": "When a bit is shifted off the end of a register during a logical shift, it wraps around and reappears at the opposite end."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": false, "explain": "A logical shift simply discards the bit that is pushed off the end — it is lost completely. Wrapping a bit to the other side is a different operation (a rotate), not a logical shift."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:1-2-4-data-storage-numbers:tf:26d9e61d', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:1-2-4-data-storage-numbers', '1.2.4 Data Storage: Numbers', 'tf', 'tf', 1, '{"question": "Overflow can occur when adding two 8-bit binary numbers if their true denary sum is greater than 255."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": true, "explain": "Correct — an 8-bit register can only store values from 0 to 255, so any true sum above 255 needs a 9th bit, which causes overflow."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:1-2-4-data-storage-numbers:tf:744bcfc4', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:1-2-4-data-storage-numbers', '1.2.4 Data Storage: Numbers', 'tf', 'tf', 1, '{"question": "Every possible byte (8 bits) can always be represented using exactly 2 hexadecimal digits."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": true, "explain": "Correct — a byte splits into exactly two 4-bit nibbles, and each nibble maps onto exactly one hexadecimal digit (0-F)."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:1-2-4-data-storage-numbers:tf:0046ca8d', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:1-2-4-data-storage-numbers', '1.2.4 Data Storage: Numbers', 'tf', 'tf', 1, '{"question": "Hexadecimal is used because computers internally store and process data as hexadecimal digits rather than binary."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": false, "explain": "Computer hardware always stores and processes data in pure binary. Hexadecimal is purely a shorthand that humans use when reading or writing binary values — it is never actually stored that way inside the machine."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:1-2-4-data-storage-numbers:learn:cfb241c5', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:1-2-4-data-storage-numbers', '1.2.4 Data Storage: Numbers', 'learn', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "How do you convert between denary and 8-bit binary?", "reading": "<h4>The 8-bit place-value ladder</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>Every position in an <strong>8-bit binary number</strong> stands for a fixed <strong>place value</strong>, exactly like the columns in a denary number stand for units, tens and hundreds.</li>\n<li>The eight place values, left to right, are always the same: <strong>128, 64, 32, 16, 8, 4, 2, 1</strong>.</li>\n<li>The left-most bit is called the <strong>most significant bit (MSB)</strong> — it carries the largest place value (128). The right-most bit is the <strong>least significant bit (LSB)</strong> — it carries the smallest place value (1).</li>\n</ul>\n<table>\n<tr><th>Place value</th><td>128</td><td>64</td><td>32</td><td>16</td><td>8</td><td>4</td><td>2</td><td>1</td></tr>\n</table>\n<h4>How do you convert denary to binary?</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>Starting from the largest place value (128), ask \"does this fit into my number?\" If yes, write a <strong>1</strong> and subtract it; if no, write a <strong>0</strong> and move on. Repeat all the way down to the 1s column.</li>\n<li>Always write the result as a full <strong>8 digits</strong>, adding leading zeros (<strong>padding</strong>) if the number doesn''t need every place — e.g. the 5-digit result 11010 must be padded to 00011010 to be a correctly-formatted 8-bit answer.</li>\n</ul>\n<table>\n<tr><th>Step</th><th>What you do</th><th>Result</th></tr>\n<tr><td>1</td><td>Convert denary 172. Find which place values from 128, 64, 32, 16, 8, 4, 2, 1 add up to 172.</td><td>128 + 32 + 8 + 4 = 172</td></tr>\n<tr><td>2</td><td>Write a 1 under every place value used, and a 0 under every place value not used.</td><td>1 0 1 0 1 1 0 0</td></tr>\n<tr><td>3</td><td>Read the 8 digits left to right as the final answer.</td><td>10101100</td></tr>\n</table>\n<h4>How do you convert binary to denary?</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>Do the reverse: line up the place values above each bit, then <strong>add together only the place values where there''s a 1</strong> — ignore every position that holds a 0.</li>\n<li>Example: 01011001 has 1s in the 64, 16, 8 and 1 columns, so 64 + 16 + 8 + 1 = <strong>89</strong>.</li>\n</ul>", "question": "What is the 8-bit binary number 01011001 in denary?", "options": ["89", "91", "93", "85"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "The 1s sit in place values 64, 16, 8 and 1: 64 + 16 + 8 + 1 = 89."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:1-2-4-data-storage-numbers:learn:3602c25f', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:1-2-4-data-storage-numbers', '1.2.4 Data Storage: Numbers', 'learn', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "How do you add two 8-bit binary numbers, and what is overflow?", "reading": "<h4>Adding binary numbers, column by column</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>Binary addition works exactly like denary column addition, except every column can only hold a 0 or a 1 — so whenever a column''s total reaches <strong>2</strong>, you write down the remainder and <strong>carry a 1</strong> into the next column left, exactly like carrying a ten in a denary sum.</li>\n<li>The four rules you need: 0+0=0, 0+1=1, 1+1=10 (write 0, carry 1), 1+1+1(carried)=11 (write 1, carry 1).</li>\n</ul>\n<pre class=\"code-block\">  01001101   (77)\n+ 00100011   (35)\n-----------\n  01110000   (112)</pre>\n<h4>What is overflow, and why does it happen?</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>An 8-bit register can only ever store the denary values <strong>0 to 255</strong>. If the TRUE result of an addition needs a 9th bit to be represented correctly, that extra bit has nowhere to go — this is called <strong>overflow</strong>.</li>\n<li>You can spot it two ways: the denary sum of the two original numbers is <strong>greater than 255</strong>, OR there is a <strong>carry left over out of the left-most (128) column</strong> once the addition finishes.</li>\n<li>When overflow happens, the 8 bits that ARE stored no longer represent the correct value — the result is simply wrong unless that extra bit is kept somewhere (e.g. a bigger register).</li>\n</ul>\n<pre class=\"code-block\">  11001000   (200)\n+ 01100100   (100)\n-----------\n1 00101100   (true result needs 9 bits: 300)</pre>\n<p>Only the right-hand 8 bits (00101100 = 44) can actually be stored in an 8-bit register — the leading 1 is lost, so the stored value (44) is not the true sum (300). That mismatch is overflow.</p>", "question": "Two 8-bit binary numbers are added and the true denary sum is 300. What happens when this is stored in an 8-bit register?", "options": ["An overflow error occurs, since 300 needs more than 8 bits to be stored correctly", "The register automatically resizes itself to become a full 9-bit register instead", "The computer rounds 300 down to the nearest value that is under 256", "Nothing unusual happens at all, because 300 fits comfortably into one byte"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "8 bits can only store 0–255, so a true result of 300 needs a 9th bit — that''s overflow. Only the low 8 bits are actually stored, giving the wrong value."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:1-2-4-data-storage-numbers:learn:15ce19b7', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:1-2-4-data-storage-numbers', '1.2.4 Data Storage: Numbers', 'learn', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "How do you convert between denary and 2-digit hexadecimal?", "reading": "<h4>What is hexadecimal?</h4>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Hexadecimal (hex)</strong> is a base-16 number system. It needs 16 different digits for each position — the familiar 0-9, then the letters <strong>A, B, C, D, E, F</strong> standing for the values 10-15.</li>\n<li>Any whole number from 0 to 255 can be written using exactly <strong>2 hexadecimal digits</strong> (00 to FF).</li>\n</ul>\n<table>\n<tr><th>Hex digit</th><td>A</td><td>B</td><td>C</td><td>D</td><td>E</td><td>F</td></tr>\n<tr><th>Value</th><td>10</td><td>11</td><td>12</td><td>13</td><td>14</td><td>15</td></tr>\n</table>\n<h4>Denary → hex</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>Divide the denary number by 16. The <strong>whole-number answer</strong> becomes the first hex digit; the <strong>remainder</strong> becomes the second hex digit (converting either one to a letter if it''s 10 or more).</li>\n</ul>\n<table>\n<tr><th>Step</th><th>What you do</th><th>Result</th></tr>\n<tr><td>1</td><td>Convert denary 219 to hex. Divide by 16.</td><td>219 ÷ 16 = 13 remainder 11</td></tr>\n<tr><td>2</td><td>Convert each part to a hex digit (13 → D, 11 → B).</td><td>D, B</td></tr>\n<tr><td>3</td><td>Write the two digits together as the final answer.</td><td>DB</td></tr>\n</table>\n<h4>Hex → denary</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>Reverse the process: multiply the FIRST hex digit''s value by 16, then add the SECOND hex digit''s value.</li>\n<li>Example: hex <strong>2F</strong> → (2 × 16) + 15 = 32 + 15 = <strong>47</strong>.</li>\n</ul>", "question": "What is the hexadecimal value 5A in denary?", "options": ["90", "85", "80", "95"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "(5 × 16) + 10 = 80 + 10 = 90."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:1-2-4-data-storage-numbers:learn:a0e3a51d', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:1-2-4-data-storage-numbers', '1.2.4 Data Storage: Numbers', 'learn', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "How do you convert between binary and hexadecimal?", "reading": "<h4>Why nibbles are the key</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>A <strong>nibble</strong> (4 bits) can represent exactly 16 different values (0000 to 1111) — precisely matching the 16 possible hexadecimal digits (0-F). That''s why hex conversion always works in groups of 4 bits.</li>\n<li>An 8-bit binary number splits into exactly <strong>two nibbles</strong>, and each nibble converts to <strong>one</strong> hex digit.</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Binary → hex</h4>\n<table>\n<tr><th>Step</th><th>What you do</th><th>Result</th></tr>\n<tr><td>1</td><td>Split 11010110 into two 4-bit nibbles.</td><td>1101 | 0110</td></tr>\n<tr><td>2</td><td>Convert each nibble to denary, then to a hex digit (8+4+1=13→D; 4+2=6→6).</td><td>D, 6</td></tr>\n<tr><td>3</td><td>Write the two hex digits together.</td><td>D6</td></tr>\n</table>\n<h4>Hex → binary</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>Reverse it: convert each hex digit into its own 4-bit nibble, then join the two nibbles together to make the full byte.</li>\n<li>Example: hex <strong>9F</strong> → 9 = 1001, F = 1111 → joined = <strong>10011111</strong>.</li>\n</ul>", "question": "What is the 8-bit binary equivalent of hexadecimal C4?", "options": ["11000100", "11000010", "10000100", "11010100"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "C = 1100, 4 = 0100 — joined together that''s 11000100."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:1-2-4-data-storage-numbers:learn:871c7981', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:1-2-4-data-storage-numbers', '1.2.4 Data Storage: Numbers', 'learn', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "What effect do logical binary shifts have?", "reading": "<h4>What is a logical shift?</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>A <strong>logical shift</strong> moves every bit in a binary number a set number of places to the <strong>left</strong> or <strong>right</strong>. Whatever gap is left behind is always filled with <strong>0</strong>s.</li>\n<li>A <strong>left shift</strong> by n places has the mathematical effect of <strong>multiplying</strong> the original value by 2ⁿ.</li>\n<li>A <strong>right shift</strong> by n places has the effect of <strong>dividing</strong> the original value by 2ⁿ (any remainder is simply lost, since binary can''t show a fraction this way).</li>\n</ul>\n<pre class=\"code-block\">00001011  (11)  shift LEFT 2 places\n00101100  (44)  → 11 × 2² = 11 × 4 = 44</pre>\n<h4>Bits shifted off the end are lost</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>Whatever bit gets pushed off the left-hand or right-hand end of the register is <strong>discarded completely</strong> — it does NOT wrap around to the other side (that''s a different operation, called a rotate, which isn''t on this specification).</li>\n<li>If a shifted-off bit was a <strong>1</strong>, the ×2ⁿ / ÷2ⁿ rule stops giving the true mathematical answer, because real information has been thrown away — this can produce <strong>inaccurate results or overflow-like data loss</strong>.</li>\n</ul>\n<pre class=\"code-block\">11100000  (224)  shift LEFT 2 places\n10000000  (128)  ← the two leading 1s are lost, so this is NOT 224 × 4 (896)</pre>", "question": "An 8-bit binary number is shifted 1 place right using a logical shift. What fills the empty bit position that is created?", "options": ["A 0", "A 1", "Whatever bit was shifted off the opposite end", "Nothing — no gap is created by a logical shift"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "Logical shifts always fill the vacated position with a 0 — the bit shifted off the far end is simply lost, not wrapped around."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:1-2-4-data-storage-numbers:learn:bfe3c112', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:1-2-4-data-storage-numbers', '1.2.4 Data Storage: Numbers', 'learn', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Why do computer scientists use hexadecimal at all?", "reading": "<h4>Hexadecimal is a shorthand for binary, nothing more</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>Computers still store and process everything in pure <strong>binary</strong> — hexadecimal is never actually stored inside the hardware. It exists purely so that <strong>humans</strong> find binary values easier to work with on paper or on screen.</li>\n<li>Because 4 bits map exactly onto 1 hex digit, a full byte that would need <strong>8 binary digits</strong> to write out can instead be written using just <strong>2 hexadecimal digits</strong> — a much more compact shorthand.</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Where this actually matters</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>Long strings of 0s and 1s are very easy to <strong>miscount or mistype</strong> by hand. Hex shortens the string, so there is far less to transcribe — and far less room for error.</li>\n<li>Hex shows up constantly in real computing: <strong>memory addresses</strong>, <strong>MAC addresses</strong>, and <strong>colour codes</strong> in web design (e.g. #FF00FF) are all just binary values written in a form that''s quicker for a person to read and communicate.</li>\n</ul>", "question": "What is the main reason hexadecimal is used instead of binary when a person reads or writes a value by hand?", "options": ["It gives a shorter, compact way to represent the same binary value, cutting down on transcription errors", "Hexadecimal numbers use noticeably less electricity for a processor to calculate with", "The computer''s memory physically stores and processes every byte as 2 hexadecimal digits, never as 8 individual binary bits", "Hexadecimal is simply an older number system that predates binary in computing history"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "Hex is purely a human-readable shorthand for binary — 2 hex digits instead of 8 bits — making values easier and safer to read, write and copy by hand. The hardware itself still only ever stores binary."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:1-2-4-data-storage-numbers:misc:d6f257f0', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:1-2-4-data-storage-numbers', '1.2.4 Data Storage: Numbers', 'misc', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Misconception check", "reading": "<p><strong>❌ Common misconception:</strong> Thinking hexadecimal digits carry on past 9 as two-character numbers like ''10'', ''11'', ''12''.</p><p><strong>✅ The correct idea:</strong> Hexadecimal only has <strong>16</strong> single-character digits in total. After 9 it switches to letters: <strong>A</strong> (10) through to <strong>F</strong> (15) — never a two-digit number like ''10'' in a single hex position.</p>", "question": "What single hexadecimal digit represents the denary value 13?", "options": ["D", "C", "E", "B"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "A=10, B=11, C=12, D=13, E=14, F=15 — so 13 is represented by the digit D."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:1-2-4-data-storage-numbers:misc:1e3fc15b', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:1-2-4-data-storage-numbers', '1.2.4 Data Storage: Numbers', 'misc', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Misconception check", "reading": "<p><strong>❌ Common misconception:</strong> Believing the MSB (most significant bit) is the right-most bit of a binary number, since it ''looks'' like the last one written.</p><p><strong>✅ The correct idea:</strong> The MSB is actually the <strong>left-most</strong> bit — it carries the largest place value (128 in an 8-bit number). The right-most bit, carrying the smallest place value (1), is the LSB.</p>", "question": "Which place value does the most significant bit (MSB) of an 8-bit number carry?", "options": ["128", "256", "64", "16"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "The MSB is the left-most bit, which always carries the largest place value in the number — 128 in an 8-bit binary number."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:1-2-4-data-storage-numbers:misc:857516fd', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:1-2-4-data-storage-numbers', '1.2.4 Data Storage: Numbers', 'misc', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Misconception check", "reading": "<p><strong>❌ Common misconception:</strong> Assuming a bit that gets shifted off the end of a register during a logical shift wraps around to reappear at the other end.</p><p><strong>✅ The correct idea:</strong> A logical shift simply <strong>discards</strong> any bit pushed off the end — it is gone completely. Making a bit reappear at the other side is a different operation entirely (a rotate), not a logical shift.</p>", "question": "During a logical shift, what happens to a bit that is pushed off the end of the register?", "options": ["It is discarded completely and cannot be recovered", "It reappears at the opposite end of the register", "It is stored temporarily in a separate carry bit", "It causes the whole shift operation to be cancelled"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "A logical shift throws away any bit pushed off the end — nothing is kept or wrapped around."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:1-2-4-data-storage-numbers:misc:82c4801f', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:1-2-4-data-storage-numbers', '1.2.4 Data Storage: Numbers', 'misc', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Misconception check", "reading": "<p><strong>❌ Common misconception:</strong> Assuming an overflow error will automatically show up as an obvious error message as soon as it happens.</p><p><strong>✅ The correct idea:</strong> Overflow usually happens <strong>silently</strong> — the register simply stores the wrong, truncated value instead of the true result. Unless a program is specifically written to check for overflow, nothing will visibly alert you that anything went wrong.</p>", "question": "What normally happens when an 8-bit addition overflows, if the program does not check for it?", "options": ["The register silently stores an incorrect, truncated value with no visible warning", "The computer automatically displays an on-screen overflow error message and halts the program", "The addition is cancelled and no result is stored anywhere at all", "The two 8-bit registers are automatically merged into one 16-bit register"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "Without a specific check written into the program, an overflow simply produces a wrong stored value — there''s no automatic warning."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:1-2-4-data-storage-numbers:misc:f93f82cb', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:1-2-4-data-storage-numbers', '1.2.4 Data Storage: Numbers', 'misc', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Misconception check", "reading": "<p><strong>❌ Common misconception:</strong> Believing hexadecimal makes a computer''s calculations run faster, or that data is actually stored as hex inside the processor.</p><p><strong>✅ The correct idea:</strong> Hardware always stores and calculates using pure <strong>binary</strong> — hexadecimal never physically exists inside the machine. It is only ever used as a shorthand for humans reading or writing binary values on paper or on screen.</p>", "question": "Why doesn''t using hexadecimal make a computer''s own calculations run any faster?", "options": ["Because the hardware only ever stores and processes data in binary, never hexadecimal", "Because hexadecimal numbers are actually larger in size than equivalent binary numbers", "Because most modern processors do not support hexadecimal arithmetic at all", "Because converting to hexadecimal always introduces small rounding errors"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "Hexadecimal is purely a human-readable shorthand — the hardware itself always stores and works with binary, so hex cannot change how fast it calculates."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:1-2-4-data-storage-numbers:misc:6b2a7f36', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:1-2-4-data-storage-numbers', '1.2.4 Data Storage: Numbers', 'misc', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Misconception check", "reading": "<p><strong>❌ Common misconception:</strong> Applying the ×2ⁿ / ÷2ⁿ shift rule automatically, without checking whether any significant (1) bits were actually shifted off the end.</p><p><strong>✅ The correct idea:</strong> The ×2ⁿ / ÷2ⁿ rule only gives the TRUE result when no 1-bits are lost off the end. If a 1-bit IS shifted off — especially during a left shift of a large value — the stored result no longer matches what ×2ⁿ would predict, because real information has been thrown away.</p>", "question": "When does the ''left shift = multiply by 2ⁿ'' rule stop giving the mathematically correct answer?", "options": ["When a 1-bit is shifted off the left-hand end of the register and lost", "Whenever the shift is performed by more than one binary place at a single time", "Whenever the original value happens to be an even number", "It always gives the correct answer, with no exceptions at all"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "If a 1-bit is pushed off the end during the shift, that information is lost — the stored result is then smaller than the true ×2ⁿ value would be."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:1-2-4-data-storage-numbers:tips:3886f7db', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:1-2-4-data-storage-numbers', '1.2.4 Data Storage: Numbers', 'tips', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "explain — Show-your-working ladder: the 2-mark conversion question", "reading": "<p>A typical question: <em>\"Convert denary 91 to a 2-digit hexadecimal number. Show your working.\"</em> [2 marks] Here is the same answer at every level:</p>\n\n<p><strong>❌ 0 marks:</strong> \"5B\"</p>\n<ul>\n<li>No working shown. Even a correct final answer with nothing behind it risks losing the working mark entirely if a small mistake creeps in.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p><strong>⚠️ 1 mark:</strong> \"91 ÷ 16 = 5 remainder 11\"</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Valid working is shown (1 mark) but the digits were never actually converted into the final hex answer and stated — the second mark is for the CONVERTED final answer.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p><strong>✅ 2 marks:</strong> \"91 ÷ 16 = 5 remainder 11 <strong>(1)</strong>. 5 stays as 5, 11 becomes B, so the answer is 5B <strong>(1)</strong>.\"</p>\n\n<p><strong>Why this matters even if your arithmetic slips:</strong> marking splits the WORKING and the ANSWER into separate marks. If your division is correct but you mislabel a remainder as the wrong letter, you keep the working mark — but only if you actually wrote the working down.</p>", "question": "You correctly work out 91 ÷ 16 = 5 remainder 11, but then wrongly write the final answer as ''511'' instead of ''5B''. What mark do you get out of 2?", "options": ["0, because the final answer written down is wrong", "1 — the working mark for the correct division step", "2, because the working clearly shows the right method throughout", "It depends entirely on whether a calculator was used"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 1, "explain": "The division step (91 ÷ 16 = 5 remainder 11) is valid working, so it earns the working mark even though the final answer was never correctly converted into hex — so the answer mark is lost."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:1-2-4-data-storage-numbers:tips:51b55b3b', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:1-2-4-data-storage-numbers', '1.2.4 Data Storage: Numbers', 'tips', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "tip — Binary addition & overflow: the checklist to work through", "reading": "<p>Whenever a question asks you to add two 8-bit binary numbers, work through this checklist before you write your final answer:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>1. Add column by column from the RIGHT.</strong> Show every carry — even a 0+0 column is worth writing out, to prove you worked through it methodically.</li>\n<li><strong>2. Check the left-most (128) column for a leftover carry.</strong> If there''s a carry left over once you''ve finished that column, that''s your signal overflow has occurred.</li>\n<li><strong>3. State your answer as a full 8 digits</strong> (or 9, if you''re specifically asked to show the overflow bit) — never drop leading zeros.</li>\n<li><strong>4. If asked to explain overflow</strong>, don''t just say \"the numbers were too big\" — say WHY: the true result needs more than 8 bits, and an 8-bit register has nowhere to put that extra bit.</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Common way to lose marks:</strong> getting every carry right, but then writing \"300\" or another denary figure as the final answer instead of the required binary string — always re-read what format the question actually wants.</p>", "question": "You correctly add two 8-bit binary numbers and get every carry right, but then write your final answer in denary instead of binary. What is the most likely outcome?", "options": ["You lose the answer mark, because the question specifically asked for a binary result", "You are automatically awarded both marks anyway, since your arithmetic was entirely correct", "You lose all marks, including the working mark, because the format is wrong", "You gain an extra mark for showing you can convert between formats"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "Working is credited separately from the final answer — but the answer still has to be given in the format the question asked for, so writing denary instead of binary loses the answer mark."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:1-2-4-data-storage-numbers:tips:7674fe17', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:1-2-4-data-storage-numbers', '1.2.4 Data Storage: Numbers', 'tips', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "explain — Binary shift questions: perform AND state, every time", "reading": "<p>Shift questions almost always ask for TWO things, and it''s easy to only give one of them.</p>\n\n<p><strong>❌ Partial answer:</strong> \"01011100\"</p>\n<ul>\n<li>A correct shifted binary result is given, but the question also asked you to STATE the mathematical effect (e.g. \"multiplies by 4\"), which is missing entirely.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p><strong>⚠️ The other half missing:</strong> \"Multiplies the value by 4\"</p>\n<ul>\n<li>States the effect correctly, but never actually performs the shift and writes the resulting binary number.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p><strong>✅ Full answer:</strong> \"00010111 shifted left 2 places = 01011100. This multiplies the original value by 2² = 4.\"</p>\n\n<p><strong>Watch for bit loss:</strong> if any 1-bit gets pushed off the end during the shift, add a sentence noting this — e.g. \"the left-most 1 is lost during this shift, so the result is no longer an exact ×4 of the original value.\" That observation is specifically credited.</p>", "question": "A question asks you to perform a logical right shift AND state its effect, worth 2 marks. You correctly write the new 8-bit binary number but don''t mention the ÷2/÷4 effect at all. What mark do you most likely get?", "options": ["1 out of 2 — the shift itself is correct but the effect was never stated", "2 out of 2, since performing the shift correctly implies you understood the effect", "0 out of 2, because both parts of a two-part question must be attempted together", "It depends entirely on how neatly the binary digits were written"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "The two parts are marked separately — a correct shifted value earns its own mark even if the effect statement is missing, but the effect mark itself is lost."}'::jsonb),
